title: Catch Me If You Can: Rocket Lab to attempt mid-air recovery again
summary: Six months after its first first-stage recovery attempt, Rocket Lab is looking to try its hand at booster recovery once again, with the launch of its 32nd mission, “Catch Me If You Can.” Liftoff is set to take place no earlier than Saturday, Nov. 5, 2022, at 6:27 AM NZDT (17:27 UTC on Friday, Nov. 4).

title: SLS returns to LC-39B for next Artemis I launch opportunity
summary: The first Space Launch System (SLS) rocket made the 6.7 km trip from High Bay 3 in the Vehicle Assembly Building (VAB) back out to Launch Complex 39B Thursday night into Friday morning. The move follows a five-week stay in the VAB to shelter from Hurricane Ian and allow teams to prepare the vehicle for its next launch attempt.

title: Virgin Galactic delays introduction of second suborbital spaceship
summary: Virgin Galactic’s second suborbital spaceplane won’t enter service in 2023 as previously planned because of demands on company personnel to both return the first spaceplane to flight and begin work on a next generation of vehicles.

title: Long March 5B rocket reenters over Pacific Ocean after forcing airspace closures in Europe
summary: A large rocket stage used to launch the final module for China’s space station made an uncontrolled reentry into the atmosphere Friday after precautionary airspace closures took effect in southern Europe.

title: SpaceX launches Hotbird 13G to extend Eutelsat’s broadcast coverage
summary: SpaceX launched the second of two satellites for Eutelsat Nov. 3 to replenish one of the largest broadcast systems in Europe, the Middle East and Northern Africa.

title: NRO to sign deals with commercial providers of hyperspectral imaging
summary: The NRO plans to soon release a request for proposals for commercial hyperspectral satellite data

title: Civilian space traffic management office coming along, but ‘don’t expect magic’
summary: OSC Director Richard DalBello said the standup of a civilian space traffic management office is moving along, but cautioned progress will be incremental

title: First Starliner crewed flight further delayed
summary: NASA has delayed the first flight of Boeing’s CST-100 Starliner commercial crew vehicle with astronauts on board, a slip that will push back the spacecraft’s first operational mission into 2024.
